  </p> 
</exercise>

  <exercise><title>Exponential graphs</title>
    <webwork source="Library/LoyolaChicago/Precalc/Chap3Sec3/Q05.pg" />
  </exercise>

  <exercise><title>Exponential graphs</title>
    <webwork source="Library/LoyolaChicago/Precalc/Chap3Sec3/Q07.pg" />
  </exercise>

<p>
Exponential functions have numerical bases with variable exponents. 
It is important to not confuse this with power functions, which are functions of the form <m>f(x)=x^n</m>. 
The following table compares and contrasts power functions from exponential functions:
</p>

<tabular halign="center">
    <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
      <cell>Power Function <m>x</m></cell>
      <cell>Exponential Function <m>y</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=x^2</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=2^x</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y=4x^3-2x+1</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=5(1.3)^x-3</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y= \sqrt x </m></cell>
      <cell><m>y=\big(\sqrt{0.85}\big)^x</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
      In this question, think of an exponential function as ONE exponential function which may have been transformed by adding, subtracting, multiplying, and/or dividing constants. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <webwork source="Library/FortLewis/Algebra/10-1-Exponential-Functions/MCH1-10-1-1thru4.pg" />
  </exercise>
  </subsection>

 <subsection><title>Euler's Number and The Natural Exponential Function</title>
  <p>
While exponential functions can have infinitely many bases, 
there is one special exponential function that we will deal with almost exclusively in our calculus classes: The Natural Exponential Function.
  </p>
  <p>
<term>The Natural Exponential Function</term><idx>Natural exponential function</idx><idx>Exponential function</idx> is nothing more than an exponential function 
whose base is the special number denoted <m>e</m>, called <term>Euler's Number</term><idx>Euler's number</idx><idx>e</idx>,  
  which is an irrational constant given by <m>e \approx 2.7182818 \ldots</m>.
  </p>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should know (memorize) a few things about the number <m>e</m>. 
      You are expected to know that <m>e</m> is irrational, with infinitely many non-repeating decimals, and <m>e \approx 2.7</m>.
    </p>
  </aside>

<p>
The natural exponential function, <m>y=e^x</m>, can be approximated by <m>y=2.718^x</m>, which can be thought of as simply an exponential function that grows 
faster than <m>y=2^x</m> but not quite as fast as <m>y=3^x.</m> 
The graph of <m>y=e^x</m> is shown in the diagram \textcolor{blue}{below(?)} along with the graphs of <m>y=2^x</m> and <m>y=3^x</m>:
</p>

<figure><title>Exponential Function - NEED SVG GRAPH</title>
  <caption><alert>Exponential Function - NEED SVG GRAPH</alert>
 The graph of <m>y=e^x</m> is shown here, along with the graphs of <m>y=2^x</m> and <m>y=3^x</m>.
  </caption>
  <title>Exponential Function - NEED SVG GRAPH</title>
  <image source="images/exponential-growth" width="70%">
  </image>
</figure>

<p>
As we can see, <m>y=e^x</m> is characteristically similar to any other exponential function, and should not be thought of as a fundamentally "different" function. 
  For our purposes, we should think of the natural exponential function as simply being an exponential function with a specific base, <m>e</m>. 
  <p>
  </p>
  The base <m>e</m> is important because with this base, the slope of the exponential function at <m>x=0</m> is exactly 1. 
  That might not sound important now, but this means that when differentiating (which we will do a lot in calculus!) 
  this means that the derivative of <m>f(x)=e^x</m> is simpler than the derivative of any other exponential function.
</p>
  </subsection>

 <subsection><title>Characteristics of Exponential Functions</title>
<p>
Just like any other type of parent function, exponential functions have a set of "default" characteristics. 
Some of these characteristics may change based on the transformations of the function, but the standard exponential function <m>f(x)=e^x</m> has the following characteristics:
</p>

<tabular halign="center">
    <row>
      <cell>Domain:</cell>
      <cell><m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Range:</cell>
      <cell><m>y \gt 0</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Horizontal asymptote:</cell>
      <cell><m>y=0</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell>Vertical asymptote:</cell>
      <cell>None</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>x</m>-intercept:</cell>
      <cell>None</cell>
    </row>
    <row>
      <cell><m>y</m>-intercept:</cell>
      <cell><m>(0,1)</m></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>

<exercise><title>Function characteristics - NEEED TO COMPLETE </title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");
      $a = random(3,6,1);
      $ans = Compute("$a*x^($a-1)");

      Context()->functions->disable('All');
      Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Checkpoint Idea: 
        An exponential function is given and students are asked to identify some of the aforementioned characteristics. 
        For instance, identify the domain, range, equation of the horizontal asymptote, y-intercept. Include exponential grwoth and exponential decay.
      </p>
    </statement>

  </webwork>
</exercise>

  </subsection>

<subsection><title>Transformations of Exponential Functions</title>
<p>
As you may have seen in your previous sudies, any parent function, <m>y=f(x)</m> can be transformed using the following parameters:
<md>y=af[k(x-d)]+c</md>
</p>
<p>
Applying these parameters to the natural exponential function, we obtain the general equation for a transformed exponential function:
<md>y=ae^{k(x-d)}+c</md>
</p>
<p>
We will focus mostly on the cases where <m>d=0</m>. 
</p>

<exercise><title>Interactive graph activity</title>
    <p>
    Click the link to see an interactive graph of a dynamic exponential function. 
    Use the sliders for the parameters <m>a</m>, <m>k</m> and <m>c</m> to see how different values of these parameters change the shape of the exponential graph.
     </p>
  <p> 
<url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/yubsxb1abl" visual="desmos.com/calculator/yubsxb1abl">Interactive Graph Activity</url>
  </p>
  <p>
    To investigate the effect of <m>a</m>, keep the other sliders fixed, and change the values of <m>a</m>. What do you notice? 
  </p> 
  <p>
    To investigate the effect of <m>k</m>, keep the other sliders fixed, and change the values of <m>k</m>. What do you notice? 
  </p>
  <p>
    To investigate the effect of <m>c</m>, keep the other sliders fixed, and change the values of <m>c</m>. What do you notice? 
  </p>
</exercise>

